WORLD CUP USA '94: ROUND OF 16; SPOTLIGHT; IT'S OVER IN BELGIUM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ISABELLE MAELCAMP, Times Brussels Bureau 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Belgians were sad and bitter about their team's exit from the World Cup after 
its 3-2 defeat by the Germans on Saturday. As expected, chief among their 
complaints is the non-call by referee Kurt Roethlisberger when Germany's Thomas 
Helmer took down Josip Weber in the penalty area in the 70th minute. 
</P>
<P>
 From Page 1 of the Walloon daily "La Derniere Heure" (The Last Hour), under 
the headline "Red card for the referee": 
</P>
<P>
 "Switzerland was famous for its banks and its chocolate. Now, she will also be 
famous due to a certain Kurt Roethlisberger, international referee, who 
distinguished himself on Saturday by refusing (Belgium) a penalty for an 
unmistakable foul by Helmer on Josip Weber." 
</P>
<P>
 Still, Belgium's first-round defeat by Saudi Arabia is linked to the Saturday 
Loss in La Libre Belgique's headline: "The Germans have finished the work of 
the Saudis." 
</P>
<P>
 Le Soir was milder, saying merely: "Superfluous regrets: the (team) comes back 
home; some trace of bitterness. . . ." 
</P>
