<HEADLINE>
<P>
ALLAN MALAMUD: NOTES ON A SCORECARD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALLAN MALAMUD 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 That was the worst 40-minute power play I've ever seen. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 It became apparent on the Fourth of July that 10 Brazilian soccer players are 
better than 11 Americans. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 The United States showed marked improvement from the 1990 World Cup tournament 
but shouldn't necessarily expect more success in 1998 in France. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 I mean, the United States hasn't won an Olympic Games medal in hockey since 
winning the gold in 1980 at Lake Placid, N.Y. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 There are no Peles on this Brazilian roster, but there are 16 players who go 
by one name and are worthy of the honor. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 Orel Hershiser and Fernando Valenzuela didn't do badly for a couple of geezers 
Sunday at Dodger Stadium. The Dodgers' 3-1 victory over Philadelphia was the 
lowest-scoring game in the major leagues that day. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 Angel rookie pitcher Brian Anderson, who has been overmatched lately, belongs 
with Dodger prospects Darren Dreifort and Chan Ho Park in the minors. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 There were some terrible choices in the fans' All-Star balloting, but the same 
kind of thing would have happened if the players and managers had voted. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 The Dodgers are the only first-place team that will be represented by only one 
player next Tuesday at Pittsburgh. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 A second-place team, Houston, leads both leagues with five selections. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 Least-known all-star in years is Astro rookie right-handed pitcher John Hudek. 
. . . 
</P>
<P>
 One of the keys to the Cincinnati Reds' success is team speed, made even more 
formidable by the acquisition of Deion Sanders. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 Funny, but Baltimore Oriole Manager Johnny Oates isn't getting any complaints 
this season for playing Cal Ripken every day. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 I'll remember Lew Hoad, who died Sunday at 59, for his performances in some 
terrific Australia-U.S. Davis Cup matches when that rivalry was one of the 
greatest in sports. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 Pete Sampras shouldn't have to apologize for being so much better than 
everyone else at Wimbledon and taking all the suspense out of the competition. 
. . . 
</P>
<P>
 ESPN's Linda Cohn described Wimbledon spectator Jack Nicholson as an "American 
werewolf in London."... 
</P>
<P>
 Running back might become a Raider strength, instead of weakness, if they 
trade for the New England Patriots' Leonard Russell. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 House of Upsets: The highest-rated male and female horses in the country, The 
Wicked North and Hollywood Wildcat, were defeated on consecutive days at 
Hollywood Park. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 The surprise winners, Slew Of Damascus in the Gold Cup on Saturday and 
Corrazona in the Triple Bend Handicap on Sunday, both got brilliant rides by 
Gary Stevens. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 Slew Of Damascus' victory in slow time enhanced the opinion of many 
handicappers that a 3-year-old will win the Breeders' Cup Classic. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 I can't think of one good reason why racing stewards consider it necessary to 
talk to the jockeys in question on the phone before ruling on an inquiry. Does 
a home plate umpire ask the batter and catcher if a pitch was inside or down 
the middle before making his call? . . . 
</P>
<P>
 UCLA diver David Fleck and All-American volleyball player Julie Bremmer have 
been awarded NCAA postgraduate scholarships. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 Eight head coaches at Pepperdine have doctorates, master's degrees or teaching 
credentials. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 Dr. Les Horvath of Glendale is celebrating the 50th anniversary of his Heisman 
Trophy, the first won by a Ohio State player. On Aug. 29, he will watch his 
Buckeyes play Fresno State in the Disneyland Pigskin Classic at Anaheim 
Stadium. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 Playing spots are still available for the second annual Maury Wills charity 
golf tournament July 21 at the Montebello Country Club. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 The best seniors not taken in the NBA draft, but who will try out as free 
agents, include center Kevin Salvadori from North Carolina, forwards Kendrick 
Warren from Virginia Commonwealth and Arturas Karnishovas from Seton Hill and 
guards Steve Woodberry from Kansas, Stevin Smith from Arizona State, Derrick 
Phelps from North Carolina and Adrian Autry from Syracuse. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 A Jorge Paez look-alike contest will be staged at the Forum Friday night 
before the Humberto (Chiquita) Gonzalez-Marcos Pacheco fight. The winner will 
receive an all-expenses paid trip to Las Vegas and tickets for the Paez-Oscar 
De La Hoya bout July 29 at the MGM Grand. The contest judge will be Paez. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 Reports in Indiana have Mike Tyson, who no longer bulks up his 5-foot-10 
frame, weighing as little as 185 pounds. 
</P>
