<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD CUP USA '94: ROUND OF 16; SPOTLIGHT; SO MUCH FOR SOCCER AS ART IN ENGLAND 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By WILLIAM TUOHY, Times London Bureau 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Daily Telegraph in London has noted that England's non-participation in 
the World Cup finals "has had a surprisingly beneficial effect on the betting 
industry, where a $75-million play is expected by the end of the tournament." 
</P>
<P>
 At William Hill (betting shops), where they anticipate an $18-million share of 
the action, spokesman Graham Sharpe said: "I think this World Cup has seen 
football betting come of age. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 "Because England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland are not there, betters 
don't need to worry about other loyalties when they put on their bets. 
</P>
<P>
 "Let's face it, the only reason for watching Bulgaria versus Bolivia -- unless 
you have an uncle from Bulgaria or an auntie from Boliva -- is because you've 
got money on it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
