<HEADLINE>
<P>
HOLLYWOOD PARK; BLUES TRAVELLER WINS AMERICAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BILL CHRISTINE, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The American Handicap became a foreign affair at Hollywood Park on Monday when 
an Irish-bred colt won the $218,000 grass race and two horses foaled in France 
were next across the finish line. 
</P>
<P>
 Blues Traveller, twice a winner at Golden Gate Fields but winless in three 
tries in Southern California, came from slightly off the pace to score a 
one-length victory, with Gothland finishing second, a half-length in front of 
Johann Quatz. Furiously, the 17-10 favorite, didn't seem to appreciate the hard 
ground and ran fourth in a field of seven, beaten by 2 1/2 lengths. 
</P>
<P>
 At 150-1, Blues Traveller finished third in last year's Epsom Derby, and two 
months later Gary Tanaka, a London investments manager, bought him for an 
undisclosed price. Blues Traveller ran once more in England, then joined 
trainer Rodney Rash in California. 
</P>
<P>
 Under Rash, Blues Traveller's biggest victory before Monday was the Rolling 
Green Handicap. In his first start at Hollywood Park, he was third behind Grand 
Flotilla and Bien Bien in the 1 1/4-mile Hollywood Turf Handicap. Chris Antley 
rode Blues Traveller last time, and Monday he became the first American jockey 
to ride him twice. 
</P>
<P>
 "I had a golden trip," Antley said. "We settled in just off Eddie 
Delahoussaye's horse (Silver Wizard, who ran sixth). This race was shorter in 
distance, and the grass was to his liking. My horse held in the stretch when 
those other horses came after us." 
</P>
<P>
 Blues Traveler won for the fourth time in 14 starts, paying $12 as the fourth 
choice. His time for 1 1/8 miles was 1:46 2/5. 
</P>
<P>
 Gothland, ridden by Corey Nakatani, also finished second to Blues Traveller in 
the Rolling Green and carried high weight of 119 pounds Monday, four more than 
the winner. 
</P>
<P>
 "Maybe he has a (distance) limit, but that's a wonderful horse," said Wally 
Dollase, who trains Gothland. "He's going to get a vacation now, and we're 
going to point him for the Breeders' Cup Mile." 
</P>
<P>
 A more immediate goal for Blues Traveller is the 1 1/4-mile Arlington Million 
on Aug. 28, with the chance that he might run one more race in between. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think this horse can handle anything from eight furlongs to a mile and a 
quarter," Rash said. "If he gets the right trip, I think he can run with the 
best grass horses in the country." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Devil His Due won the $350,000 Suburban Handicap at Belmont Park by a 
half-length over Valley Crossing. 
</P>
<P>
 Devil His Due, winner of the Brooklyn Handicap last month, carried high weight 
of 124 pounds and was hard-pressed to hold off Valley Crossing, who carried 
only 113. Devil His Due, ridden by Mike Smith, paid $3.60 at Belmont and $4 at 
Hollywood Park, running 1 1/4 miles in 2:02 2/5 and earning $210,000 to 
increase his bankroll to $3.3 million. 
</P>
<P>
 Kingdom Found, who went to Belmont because trainer Gary Jones didn't like his 
weight assignment for Saturday's Hollywood Gold Cup, led for a half-mile but 
quit running when Devil His Due passed him. He finished last in the five-horse 
field. 
</P>
<P>
 Despite Devil His Due's recent achievements, the 5-year-old was no match for 
Holy Bull, the 3-year-old colt who easily defeated older horses in the 
Metropolitan Handicap at Belmont on May 30. 
</P>
<P>
 Horse Racing Notes 
</P>
<P>
 The Suburban and the American handicaps were the first and last races in the 
National Best Seven, which hasn't caught on and drew a handle of only $306,593 
Monday. No one picked all seven winners and 15 50-cent tickets on six winners 
were worth $4,586.65 apiece. The other winners were Dinner in Rio (9-1) in the 
Ft. McHenry Handicap at Laurel, Hey Hazel (8-1) in the Molly Pitcher Handicap 
at Monmouth Park, Marastani (7-1) in the Stars and Stripes Handicap at 
Arlington, Country Coy (6-1) in the Americana Handicap at Calder and Empire 
Pool (13-10) in the Independence Handicap at Louisiana Downs. . . . After six 
weeks, the jackpot carry-over pool, which is paid if there's only one 
seven-horse winning ticket, is $92,774. . . . The Daily Racing Form's cover 
price has gone up 15 cents to $3, plus tax. 
</P>
</TEXT>
