<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: TUSTIN; COUNCIL MEMBERS TO DEBATE TERM LIMITS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALAN EYERLY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 City Council members will debate their own fates tonight as they argue about 
how many terms they can serve before they are required to leave the council. 
</P>
<P>
 The council already has approved a ballot measure that, if passed by voters in 
November, would limit council members to two four-year terms. 
</P>
<P>
 But Mayor Thomas R. Saltarelli wants to give residents the option of voting on 
another measure that would limit council members to three consecutive terms. 
</P>
<P>
 Saltarelli and Councilman Jeffery M. Thomas assert that a limit of two terms 
would weaken Tustin's clout on county and regional boards that operate on a 
seniority basis. 
</P>
<P>
 But Mayor Pro Tem Jim Potts, who thinks a three-term limit is too long, 
contends that the city wouldn't lose any more influence with shorter term 
limits. 
</P>
<P>
 Also on the agenda for the 7 p.m. council meeting is a proposed ordinance that 
would regulate public nudity, though Potts said he didn't know of any incidents 
of public nudity occurring in the city that would have prompted the measure. 
</P>
<P>
 Acting City Atty. Lois E. Jeffrey said the ordinance "reflects the latest 
thinking of the United States Supreme Court on the issue" and that it would 
give Tustin "more effective tools for regulating public nudity than exist in 
the current city code." 
</P>
<P>
 The ordinance would not apply to establishments devoted to theatrical 
performances, which could include topless bars. 
</P>
<P>
 The council also is scheduled to consider a measure prohibiting public 
officials from accepting gifts from people who do business with the city. 
</P>
<P>
 If the gift ban is approved, the council also would have to amend the city's 
conflict-of-interest code. 
</P>
<P>
 The council, in addition, will discuss a proposed ballot measure that would 
allow voters to decide if the city's solid-waste disposal contract should be 
put out to bid every five years. 
</P>
<P>
 Potts said a competitive bidding process would result in cost savings for 
Tustin. 
</P>
<P>
 "If it was open to bid, we'd get a much better deal for the city," he 
maintained. ALAN EYERLY 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA070594-0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 057780 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
