<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: SEAL BEACH; HUMANE SOCIETY OUT TO LICENSE PETS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SHELBY GRAD 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Workers from the Humane Society will canvass city streets over the next few 
weeks in a campaign to encourage pet owners to obtain licenses for their dogs 
and cats. 
</P>
<P>
 All neighborhoods in the city will be targeted, said City Manager Jerry L. 
Bankston, who estimated that 15% to 20% of Seal Beach pets do not have proper 
registrations. 
</P>
<P>
 The city will spend about $6,000 on the effort but expects to receive $15,000 
in new pet license fees, Bankston said. 
</P>
<P>
 The push to license pets comes as the city recently set up a new computer 
system that will store all animal control records. 
</P>
<P>
 Pet owners will be able to purchase licenses from the Humane Society workers, 
who also will distribute information about rabies vaccinations. SHELBY GRAD 
</P>
