<HEADLINE>
<P>
HOMELESSNESS IN THE VALLEY / SURVIVING DAY BY DAY; VALLEY HOMELESS; ESCALATING 
NUMBERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by maki becker 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 According to statistics compiled by the Los Angeles County Department of 
Public Social Services, the State of California Department of Social Services 
and the Los Angeles Mobile Ombudsman Program: 
</P>
<P>
 On any given night in LA County, there are between 43,233 and 77,143 people 
who are homeless 
</P>
<P>
 On any given night in LA County, there are around 15,117 homeless family 
members, 10,738 of which are children Contributing Circumstances 
</P>
<P>
 Last year, out of 136 families that lived at The Trud and Norman Louis Valley 
Shelter: 
</P>
<P>
 30 lost jobs immediately prior to becoming homeless 
</P>
<P>
 29 were unable to find employement 
</P>
<P>
 96 on some kind of public assistance 
</P>
<P>
 37 formally evicted 
</P>
<P>
 12 victims of domestic violence 
</P>
<P>
 2 from out of the city 
</P>
<P>
 6 from out of state HOW CAN I HELP? 
</P>
<P>
 LOAVES AND FISHES 
</P>
<P>
 21600 Hart St., Canoga Park 91303; 340-2050 
</P>
<P>
 511 Kalisher St., San Fernando 91340; 365-3195 
</P>
<P>
 4322 San Fernando Rd., Glendale 91205; 956-1857 
</P>
<P>
 14525 Delano St., 102, Van Nuys 91411; 997-0943 
</P>
<P>
 A non-profit, independent organization with strong links to the Catholic 
church. Provides food, clothing, case management, rental assistance and 
short-term motel shelter. 
</P>
<P>
 Donations: Non-perishable foods, clothing and money to be dropped off at one 
of the four locations. 
</P>
<P>
 Volunteer help: Preparing bags of foods, stocking shelves, sorting through 
clothes, interviewing clients for application to check for eligibility and 
referring them to other agencies and services. 
</P>
<P>
 * M.E.N.D. 
</P>
<P>
 13460 Van Nuys Blvd., Pacoima 91331; 896-0246 
</P>
<P>
 Helps homeless and low-income persons. 
</P>
<P>
 Donations: Non-perishable foods, clothing, toiletries, blankets, bottled water 
and money. 
</P>
<P>
 Volunteer help: Sorting donated items, packing food boxes, distributing food 
and clothing and interviewing clients. (contact: Maria Franco) 
</P>
<P>
 * The Trudy and Norman Louis Valley Shelter 7843 Lankershim Blvd., North 
Hollywood 91605; 765-0442 
</P>
<P>
 Provides emergency, transistional and permanent housing for families. 
Facilities include one classroom and a free medical clinic. 
</P>
<P>
 Donations: All foods, new toys, used computers, furniture, appliances, plates, 
pots, pans and money. 
</P>
<P>
 Volunteer help: Assisting teacher in tutoring, clerical help, answering 
telephones, preparing, serving, cleaning in the cafeteria and sorting donated 
items. 
</P>
<P>
 * The Church On the Way 
</P>
<P>
 14300 Sherman Way, Van Nuys 91405; 779-8000 
</P>
<P>
 A homeless outreach program operating out of The Church on the Way, but soon 
to be a seperate, non-religiously organization. Currently trying to establish a 
center with a clinic which is equipped with showers. 
</P>
<P>
 Donations: Money, food, and clothing. 
</P>
<P>
 Volunteer help: Physicians needed to volunteer their time, and people 
interested in networking with other orgnazations to best serve the needs of the 
homeless. 
</P>
<P>
 * BURBANK TEMPORARY AID SHELTER 
</P>
<P>
 1304 W. Burbank Blvd., Burbank 91506; 846-2330 
</P>
<P>
 Serves the homeless and needy in the Burbank area. 
</P>
<P>
 Donations: Food, funds for lodging, clothing. 
</P>
<P>
 Volunteer help: Needs help in their its pantry and working directly with 
clients. Especially encourages senior citizens to volunteer their time. 
</P>
<P>
 * TARZANA TREATMENT CENTER 
</P>
<P>
 18846 Oxnard St., Tarzana 91356; 996-1051 
</P>
<P>
 An alcohol and drug treatment center that particpates in some outreach 
programs for the homeless.  
</P>
<P>
 Donations: Money, tools, office supplies and equipment (ask for donations 
division) 
</P>
<P>
 * INDEPENDENT LIVING CENTER 
</P>
<P>
 14354 Haynes Street, Van Nuys 91401; 785-6934 
</P>
<P>
 Works with disabled adults to help them live independently. Much of the 
homeless population is made up of disabled people. 
</P>
<P>
 Donations: Food, especially non-perishable items 
</P>
<P>
 Volunteer help: Needs people to be on the look-out for cheap housing, to 
repair broken items, as well as people skilled in crisis counselling and to 
function as big brothers or sisters. 
</P>
<P>
 * SAN FERNANDO VALLEY COMMUNITY MENTAL HEALTH CENTER Cornerstone: 6728 Van 
Nuys Blvd., Van Nuys 91405;901-4830 
</P>
<P>
 The Harbour: 15301 Lanark St., Panorama City 91402 
</P>
<P>
 The Harbour and Cornerstone are programs of the mental health center dedicated 
to helping out mentally ill men who are homeless. 
</P>
<P>
 Donations: All types of foods, boxed drinks, clothing such as sweatshirts, 
jeans and tennis shoes, blankets and umbrellas. 
</P>
<P>
 Volunteer help: People to come share their talents--music, drawing or 
sewing--for a couple of hours a week and help answering phones. 
</P>
<P>
 * UNITED WAY 
</P>
<P>
 6851 Lennox Avenue, Van Nuys 91405; 908-5000 
</P>
<P>
 Offers an organized way for people to give money to non-profit organizations 
in the community. 
</P>
<P>
 Donations: Relies mostly on monetary contributions. 
</P>
<P>
 Volunteers: Clerical tasks and also people to serve on a long-term basis on 
decision-making teams. 
</P>
<P>
 * SALVATION ARMY 
</P>
<P>
 14917 Victory Blvd., Van Nuys 91411; 781-5739 
</P>
<P>
 Provides meals to homeless and needy through its soup kitchen and vans. 
</P>
<P>
 Donations: Needs especially food but also takes money. 
</P>
<P>
 Volunteer help: Distributing soup and sandwiches by van and clean-up at the 
kitchen. 
</P>
<P>
 * WOMEN'S CARE COTTAGE 
</P>
<P>
 P.O. Box 451, Van Nuys 91408; 786-7830 
</P>
<P>
 Shelter for homeless women and children 
</P>
<P>
 Donations: Food, clothing, household items like plates, pans and linens 
</P>
<P>
 Volunteer help: Work one day a week to provide meal services, distribute 
clothing, collect donations and interact with clients. 
</P>
<P>
 * VALLEY MAYOR'S FUND FOR THE HOMELESS 
</P>
<P>
 5323 Leghorn Ave., Sherman Oaks 91401; 784-4357 
</P>
<P>
 A volunteer referral service that was involved in printing the homeless help 
cards. 
</P>
<P>
 Donations: Takes monetary donations but prefers people particpate in their 
many fundraisers. 
</P>
<P>
 * SEPULVEDA UNITED METHODIST CHURCH 
</P>
<P>
 15435 Rayen St., North Hills 91343; 892-1164 
</P>
<P>
 This church provides breakfast and showers three mornings a week to the 
homeless from 8 to 9 a.m. Mondays, Wednesdays and Fridays. Any spare food is 
left on a self-help counter. 
</P>
<P>
 Donations: Towels, shampoo, soap, razors, tooth brushes and paste, pancake 
mix, coffee, tang, sugar and other breakfast foods. 
</P>
<P>
 Volunteer help: Anyone interested should show up at 7 a.m. at the kitchen door 
and you will be put to work. 
</P>
<P>
 * SAN FERNANDO VALLEY INTERFAITH COUNCIL 
</P>
<P>
 10824 Topanga Canyon Blvd., Chatsworth 91311; 718-6460 
</P>
<P>
 Coordinates congregations throughout the valley to provide shelter for 
homeless in chruch santuaries and offers meals, counselling and referrals. 
</P>
<P>
 Donations: Food and money 
</P>
<P>
 Volunteer help: Coordinating sanctuary shelters, information referrals, 
preparing meals and outreach to homeless seniors. 
</P>
<P>
 * EL CENTRO DE AMNISTAD 
</P>
<P>
 7024 Deering Street, Canoga Park 91305; 347-8565 
</P>
<P>
 Offers referrals to shelters, counselling and food/clothing bank. 
</P>
<P>
 Donations: Food (especially fruit and vegetables) and money 
</P>
<P>
 Volunteer help: Answering phones (bilingual people especially useful), 
opeating computers and working with youths. 
</P>
<P>
 * BETTER VALLEY SERVICES 
</P>
<P>
 8000 Laurel Canyon Blvd., North Hollywood 91605; 767-1128 Provides food and 
supplies to the homeless and features one of the only services for placing 
homeless persons with pets in shelters. 
</P>
<P>
 Donations: Money, non-perishable foods, cleaning supplues, office equipment, 
towels, linens, blankets and bottled water. 
</P>
<P>
 Volunteer help: Office work, outreach to homeless, picking up donations and 
researching referrals. 
</P>
<P>
 * PROYECTO ESPERANZA 10264 Rincon Ave., Pacoima 91331; 834-2214 
</P>
<P>
 One of two homes in the Los Angeles area that specifically targets young 
Latino men who are homeless. These men are taught job skills during their three 
month stay. 
</P>
<P>
 Donations: Food, games, radios, alarm clocks, tools, furniture, blankets, 
bedsheets, towels, toothbrushes, toothpaste and juice. 
</P>
<P>
 Volunteer help: Teaching English and spending time talking with the men. 
Volunteers do not need to speak Spanish. 
</P>
<P>
 * UNIVERSAL RESCUE MISSION 623 1/2 Brand St., Glendale 91204; 548-8915 
</P>
<P>
 Features an outreach program for the homeless referred to it by other 
organizations and finds shelter for them and helps in job search process. 
Donations: Money, clothing, non-perishable foods and periodically furniture. 
</P>
<P>
 Volunteer help: Call the mission to be put on a list for help doing special 
projects like distributing food at local parks. 
</P>
